    <!-- Content sections -->
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff" padding-bottom="6px">
      <mj-column>
       <mj-spacer height="18px"></mj-spacer>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">
        Korea’s grocery revolution
        </h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
       In 2011, long before online shopping became the norm, Tesco pulled a masterstroke in Seoul, South Korea. By then, South Korea already had a 96% internet penetration and 91% smartphone usage. Also, around 65% of the population used public transport daily, and Tesco identified an opening. 
          </p>
        </mj-text> 

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/tesco-asia-expansion-history.jpg" alt="Tesco's expansion into Asia has been an essential focus for the company since the late 1990" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>
            Tesco's expansion into Asia has been an essential focus for the company since the late 1990s. Credits: Lildoremi.org</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
           The British retail giant launched the <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-14-06-2025-worlds-first-virtual-store?source=website" target="_blank">world’s first virtual store</a>, which was innovative, effective, and wildly successful. Tesco rolled out wall-length billboards designed to resemble supermarket shelves. Commuters could scan QR codes using Tesco’s Homeplus app. The items were in their online basket and could even deliver them the same day.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;filter:blur(5px);">
            Tesco understood local behavior and pain points, then offered an innovative and practical resolution. Homeplus became the most downloaded shopping app in South Korea, with over 900,000 downloads. Online trade jumped by 130% and registered users increased by 76%. Virtual stores also meant fewer physical locations, less inventory waste, and greater efficiency. Smaller physical hubs could serve as pickup points without needing to stock full shelves.
            </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
